Hi all,

According to [1], sched_rt_period_us defaults to 1_000_000 microseconds, so prior to this commit sched_rt_runtime_us was equal to sched_rt_period_us.

I took a brief look at the kernel's code, but due to the complexity of the code, I could not come to a firm conclusion at this point. My understanding *used to be* that making the sched_rt_runtime_us equal to sched_rt_period_us is similar to setting sched_rt_runtime_us to -1. However, while looking at the code, I also saw that a lot functions short-circuit when the value -1 is used for sched_rt_runtime_us, so it is possible that my earlier understanding was incorrect.

I also experimented with a test program similar to the following in a VM:

```
int main(int argc, char *argv[]) {
  volatile unsigned long long i, j;
  for (i = 0; i < 3000ULL; i++) {
    for (j = 0; j < 1000000ULL; j++) {
      (void)j;
    }
  }
  return 0;
}
```

I ran the test program twice on an isolated core, with sched_rt/99 scheduling class/priority, once with sched_rt_runtime_us=-1, and once with sched_rt_runtime_us=1000000 (i.e., equal to sched_rt_period_us), with commands like the following:

```
sysctl -w kernel.sched_rt_runtime_us=1000000
taskset -c 2 chrt -f 99 /usr/bin/time -v /home/sysadmin/test_sched_loop
sysctl -w kernel.sched_rt_runtime_us=-1
taskset -c 2 chrt -f 99 /usr/bin/time -v /home/sysadmin/test_sched_loop
```

In both cases, the RT throttling message did not appear in dmesg, and both "time" commands indicated zero non-voluntary context switches.

I will invite a few colleagues to the code review for better insight.

Nevertheless, it would be great if the commit message could be updated to indicate the intent and the reason for making this change. Thank you.

[1] https://git.kernel.org/pub/scm/linux/kernel/git/stable/linux.git/tree/kernel/sched/core.c?h=v5.10.99#n73

